title: Google colab crashes when trying to load the model (containing a custom operator) for inferencing using ORT.
body:
Hi @askhade @pranavsharma 

**Describe the bug**
I have been wanting to test the inference times of a custom operator as described [here](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/3205).
I was asked to chose either of the methods.
1.Make changes to the onnx sub-module in onnxruntime/cmake/external/ so that ORT thinks it as an official operator and continue the registartion and kernel implementation in ORT.
2.Register the custom op as a contrib_op. (Works)

Initially, I tried defining an operator in ONNX named DQL, which is just a copy of the DynamicQuantizeLinear in ONNX and followed its implementation in ORT as shown here,
microsoft/onnxruntime@d84799e . and DQL works fine while inferencing in ORT.

However, when I followed the first approach for implementing my custom op(an activation fn), and tried to inference the graph (built with the help of helper.make_node and helper.make_graph in onnx) google colab crashes while loading the model.

> sess = rt.InferenceSession("Mkcustom.onnx")

I have followed the approach in onnxruntime/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/activation/activations.cc , activations.h , and onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/cpu_execution_provider.cc 
and added the op schema to onnx and onnx submodule in ORT.

**Urgency**
Very Urgent.



**Expected behavior**
The operator is supposed to successfully load into the session and inferencing should be done, but instead google colab crashes.

- This is a feature request from 1p customer
- When EP::Compile fails, currently we will fail the entire execution, add a way to let the particular partition which fails the EP::Compile fall back to next EP

title: [java] Fix build.gradle so it always targets Java 8 class files.
body:
**Description**: 

This adds the `--release 8` flag to all javac commands when running on JDK 9 or newer. That flag ensures that only Java 8 methods are used as well as emitting class files which are Java 8 compatible, instead of using the old `--source 1.8 --target 1.8` mechanism which only ensures the latter.

If we bump the version of Gradle to 6.6 or later then there is a simpler way of doing this - https://docs.gradle.org/6.6/userguide/building_java_projects.html#sec:java_cross_compilation, but I don't know what version of gradle the android build depends on.

Fixes #6584.

title: InvalidGraph: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 10 : INVALID_GRAPH : Load model from Models/onnx_mutate_2.onnx failed:This is an invalid model. Error in Node:c1 : Required attribute 'to' is missing.
body:
**Describe the bug**
Created an Onnx model using helper functions but unable to load the model in Onnxruntime. The model consists of 2 columns that need to be casted from string to float data types.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows 10
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): pip
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.6.0
- Python version: 3.7.9

**To Reproduce**
```
I1 = helper.make_tensor_value_info('I1', TensorProto.STRING, [1, 1])
I2 = helper.make_tensor_value_info('I2', TensorProto.STRING, [1, 1])

# Create one output (ValueInfoProto)
X1 = helper.make_tensor_value_info('X1', TensorProto.FLOAT, [1, 1])
X2 = helper.make_tensor_value_info('X2', TensorProto.FLOAT, [1, 1])

node_def = helper.make_node(
    'Cast', # node name
    ['I1'], # inputs
    ['X1'], # outputs
    name='c1'
)

node_def_2 = helper.make_node(
    'Cast', # node name
    ['I2'], # inputs
    ['X2'], # outputs
    name='c2'
)

# Create the graph (GraphProto)
graph_def_2 = helper.make_graph(
    [node_def, node_def_2],
    'test-model',
    [I1, I2],
    [X1, X2],
)
model_def_2 = helper.make_model(graph_def_2, producer_name='onnx-example-2')
onnx.save(model_def_2, 'Models/onnx_mutate_2.onnx')

sess = rt.InferenceSession("Models/onnx_mutate_2.onnx")
```
**Expected behavior**
Expecting the ort to load the model. And the following prediction to run properly.
```
sess = rt.InferenceSession("Models/onnx_mutate_2.onnx")
pred_onx = sess.run(['X1', 'X2'], {'I1': [['6']], 'I2':[['2']]})[0]
print(pred_onx)
```

**Screenshots**
If applicable, add screenshots to help explain your problem.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15011367/107130984-c74fb580-68f8-11eb-9650-ceaede5b728d.png)

title: Make kernel hash stable in type reduced build
body:
**Description**: 
Add infrastructure so that a kernel definition has the full list of supported types and a list of types enabled in this build. We need to use the full list when calculating the kernel hash so that the hash value in an ORT format model is stable across builds with and without type reduction enabled.

Update the kernels that support type reduction within the kernel implementation to provide both lists.

**Motivation and Context**
ORT format model created with a full build (which is the typical usage) would have a different hash for a kernel than a type reduced build due to the type constraints changing. This would prevent the model from being able to be loaded.

title: Only update the excluded ops/types if args.update is true.
body:
**Description**: 
Don't update the excluded ops/types unless args.update is true. Updating the exclusion info triggers rebuilding of all kernels using type reduction, which causes unnecessary rebuilding. 

**Motivation and Context**
Unnecessary increase in build time when providing just the '--build' flag.

title: MLTypeCallDispatcher binary size reduction
body:
**Description**
Move ORT_ENFORCE()'s within MLTypeCallDispatcher to helper class functions to reduce the size of function names in ORT_ENFORCE().
ORT_ENFORCE() captures the containing function's name in the error message. For some usages of MLTypeCallDispatcher (i.e., with numerous types or long type names), the function name is quite long and can contribute significantly to the binary size. Usage in the Cast CPU kernel is a notable example.
This change moves the ORT_ENFORCE() checks from a class template member function template with variable length name to a helper function with a fixed length name.

**Motivation and Context**
Reduce binary size.

title: Reduce tensorprotoutils binary size
body:
**Description**: 
Refactor a few aspects of tensorprotoutils to reduce the binary size.
  - Move type agnostic code outside of templatized code
    - external and raw data reads are based on number of bytes and don't need the actual type for the low level read
    - if an initializer has external data, UnpackInitializerData can read that first in type agnostic code prior to any templatized code
  - Make the setup of the two UnpackTensor variants equivalent
    - defined and instantiated in .cc 
    - Also checked that the linker is able to throw away unused instantiations from a MinSizeRel build by commenting out the ConstantOfShape registration and changing the type list in matmal_scale_fusion.cc (the two current external usages of UnpackTensor).
  - Remove some redundant/duplicate checks
  - Clarify some naming as to whether something refers to number of elements vs number of bytes
  - Add unit tests for more external data types
  - Minor change to use uint8_t for bytes in a few places instead of char. 
    - The data isn't signed per-se, so uint8_t is a slightly better fit (and shorter to type than unsigned char).

Reductions: 16.2 KB in Windows release build. 

**Motivation and Context**
Reduce binary size growth from adding external data support in more places.

title: Revert "Remove abs in LpPool (#6303)"
body:
This reverts commit 3b3e698674dca2014b91fb617e2c4f22ffd0c5c9.

The reason for this revert is as follows:
Even though the logic introduced ***may be*** the right logic for LpPool (as pointed out in #6302), the ONNX spec is very ambiguous about this. It states that "Lp pooling consisting of computing the ***Lp norm*** on all values of a subset of the input....",. Lp norm itself requires using an `abs()` as it is the equivalent of - https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.linalg.norm.html, https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/norm, and https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/generated/torch.norm.html. 

Given the ambiguity and given that this change breaks tests in DML, it makes sense to keep the logic as it was in the previous releases, clarify the spec in ONNX (with tests), and then change the logic here.

title: Java runtime request: Add method that returns underlying map for OrtSession.Result
body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
This is specific to the Java ONNX runtime.
I have two models built with ONNX, model A and model B. I use the ONNX Runtime Java API to load these models and make inferences with them. The workflow is that I need to compute a prediction with model A and then feed the result from model A into model B. When I call resultFromA = A.run(inputs) the API returns a Result. Ideally I'd like to take that result and call B.run(resultFromA) but run only accepts Map<String, OnnxTensor> inputs. Do I really have to iterate over resultFromA and put its contents into a new Map? Or is it possible to add a method in Result that will return a map that I can use to call run on model B?

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version (you are using):
1.6.0

**Describe the solution you'd like**
Add a method to Result that returns a map like Map<String, OnnxTensor>. Result already has an underlying map so I think you can do this easily.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
The alternative is to rebuild the map using the available methods in Result like so:
    Map<String, OnnxTensor> modelAMap = new HashMap<String, OnnxTensor>();
    modelAResults.forEach(e -> modelAMap.put(e.getKey(), (OnnxTensor) e.getValue()));

**Additional context**
This request is related to SO question here: [How to most efficiently feed one ONNX model's output into another in java?](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/66073055/how-to-most-efficiently-feed-one-onnx-models-output-into-another-in-java?noredirect=1#comment116959024_66073055)

title: Support multiple dynamic inputs in custom ops
body:
**Description**: 
Support multiple dynamic typed inputs in custom ops. #6066 enabled support for dynamic typed inputs/outputs but there was a minor limitation in the implementation. For illustrative purposes, if there was a dynamic input 1 (returned `ONNX_TENSOR_ELEMENT_DATA_TYPE_UNDEFINED`  for the type) that was actually `int8` in a node and if there was another dynamic input 2 that is `uint8` in the same node, the current implementation would return an error while loading the model: `Type (T) bound to different types` because we were essentially binding only one type template parameter `T` for all the dynamic inputs. This change supports multiple type template parameters `T0`...`Tn` because they need not be inter-dependent at all.

Also, added a couple of important checks:
1) If an output was dynamic typed, there must be atleast one dynamic typed input from which we may be able to infer the type of the output at runtime. (This assertion was missing in the original implementation and it basically allowed a dynamic typed output without any dynamic typed inputs).

2) If there are more than 1 dynamic typed inputs, there cannot be any dynamic typed outputs as type inference is now impossible for the generic case. There may be multiple dynamic typed inputs as long as the types of the outputs are all fixed. (#6469 requests support for this exact case)  

**Motivation and Context**
Resolves https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/6469
Good to include this enhancement for 1.7 given that this feature (dynamic inputs/outputs for custom ops) will ship in 1.7
